cell("markdown","# Algorithms 31: Breadth-First and Depth-First Search\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Represent a Graph using Adjacency Lists and Adjacency Matrices\n2. Implement Breadth-First Search (BFS) using a Queue\n3. Implement Depth-First Search (DFS) using a Stack or Recursion\n4. Differentiate the use-cases for BFS vs DFS\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 15\n**Estimated time:** 60 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 31"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### Graph Representations\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 31:* A graph is a set of vertices (nodes) and edges (connections). Edges can be directed or undirected.\n\nTo represent a graph in code, we generally use an **Adjacency List** (a dictionary mapping each node to a list of its neighbors) or an **Adjacency Matrix** (a 2D grid where `matrix[i][j]` is 1 if an edge exists, 0 otherwise).\n\n### Graph Traversal: BFS vs DFS\nTo explore a graph, we need a systematic way to visit all reachable nodes without getting stuck in infinite loops.\n- **Breadth-First Search (BFS)**: Explores all neighbors of a node before moving deeper. It ripples outwards like a wave. It is guaranteed to find the *shortest path* in an unweighted graph. It uses a **Queue** (First-In, First-Out).\n- **Depth-First Search (DFS)**: Plunges as deep as possible down one path before backtracking. It is great for maze-solving and detecting cycles. It uses a **Stack** (Last-In, First-Out), which can be managed explicitly or via the recursive call stack."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\nIf you want to find the fastest route out of a maze, should you use BFS or DFS? What if you want to find ALL possible routes out of the maze?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answer</summary>\nUse **BFS** to find the absolute fastest route, because it naturally explores shorter paths before longer ones. Use **DFS** to exhaustively find all possible routes, because it easily traces single paths from start to finish and then backtracks.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Adjacency List to Matrix\nConvert the following adjacency list into a 2D adjacency matrix representation.\n`adj_list = {0: [1, 2], 1: [2], 2: [0, 3], 3: []}`"),
cell("code","def list_to_matrix(adj_list):\n    n = len(adj_list)\n    matrix = [[0] * n for _ in range(n)]\n    # Iterate through adj_list and populate matrix\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    return matrix\n\n# print(list_to_matrix({0: [1, 2], 1: [2], 2: [0, 3], 3: []}))"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 1 — Algorithm Construction\n\n### Step 1: Breadth-First Search (BFS)\nWrite a function `bfs(graph, start_node)` that prints out the nodes in BFS order.\nUse a `collections.deque` for $O(1)$ pop from the front, and a `set` to track `visited` nodes."),
cell("code","def bfs(graph, start):\n    queue = deque([start])\n    visited = set([start])\n    order = []\n    \n    while queue:\n        # 1. Pop from the LEFT of the queue\n        # curr = queue.popleft()\n        # 2. Add to order\n        # 3. For each neighbor of curr in graph:\n        #      If not visited, mark visited and append to queue\n        # YOUR CODE HERE\n        pass\n        \n    return order"),
